Matt Fandler was at the controls of one of two single-engine planes that were flying over Superior, Wisconsin, with a group of experienced skydivers who were making their last jump of the day, during an interview last month.

But what was supposed to be a moment of perfectly-timed
 air acrobatics and exhilarating free-falls turned into a terrifying 
jump-for-your-life situation when Fandler's Cessna suddenly sandwiched on top 
of the other.

